<h3 id="asides">Asides</h3>

<p>Standard HTML5 <code>&lt;aside&gt;</code> elements are enhanced with a set of classes to flexibly position them relative to content. This approach removes the need for a dedicated sidebar. The <code>&lt;aside&gt;</code> element is often used to wrap <code>&lt;figure&gt;</code> elements, but can equally wrap any tangential content.</p>

<p><strong>Note:</strong> These asides are only designed to work inside the default compressed content column, not the medium or full-width variants.</p>

<pre><code>&lt;aside class="{alignment}"&gt;
    ...
&lt;/aside&gt;
</code></pre>

<h4>Aside variants</h4>

<ul>
    <li><strong>Align centre</strong><br>
        Modifier class: <code>.align-centre</code> or <code>.align-center</code><br>
        Centre the <code>&lt;aside&gt;</code> inside the content column.
    </li>
    <li><strong>Align left</strong><br>
        Modifier class: <code>.align-left</code><br>
        Align <code>&lt;aside&gt;</code> to the left of the content column.
    </li>
    <li><strong>Align right</strong><br>
        Modifier class: <code>.align-right</code><br>
        Align <code>&lt;aside&gt;</code> to the right of the content column.
    </li>
    <li><strong>Extend left</strong><br>
        Modifier class: <code>.extend-left</code><br>
        Float to left and span the content column and the 2 left grid columns. Since no width is set, the <code>&lt;aside&gt;</code> takes on the width of the content it contains.
    </li>
    <li><strong>Extend right</strong><br>
        Modifier class: <code>.extend-right</code><br>
        Float to right and span the content column and the 2 right grid columns. Since no width is set, the <code>&lt;aside&gt;</code> takes on the width of the content it contains.
    </li>
    <li><strong>Float left</strong><br>
        Modifier class: <code>.float-left</code><br>
        Float left.
    </li>
    <li><strong>Float right</strong><br>
        Modifier class: <code>.float-right</code><br>
        Float right.
    </li>
    <li><strong>Parallel left</strong><br>
        Modifier class: <code>.parallel-left</code><br>
        Place the <code>&lt;aside&gt;</code> in the left 2 grid columns directly parallel to the content that it precedes.
    </li>
    <li><strong>Parallel right</strong><br>
        Modifier class: <code>.parallel-right</code><br>
        Place the <code>&lt;aside&gt;</code> in the right 2 grid columns directly parallel to the content that it precedes.
    </li>
</ul>

<h3 id="end-piece">End piece</h3>

<p>Long-form content articles should end with the end piece sub-pattern. It shows a square box with the date the article was published.</p>

<pre><code>&lt;p class="end"&gt;{{formatDate date "%A %d %B %Y"}}&lt;/p&gt;
</code></pre>


<h3 id="lead-paragraph">Lead paragraph</h3>

<p>The opening <code>&lt;h1&gt;</code> is typically followed by a lead paragraph.</p>

<pre><code>&lt;p class="lead"&gt;Duis aute irure dolor in reprehenderit in voluptate velit esse cillum dolore eu fugiat nulla pariatur. Excepteur sint occaecat cupidatat non proident, sunt in culpa qui officia deserunt mollit anim id est laborum.&lt;/p&gt;
</code></pre>


<h3 id="pull-quotes">Pull quotes</h3>

<p>Pull quotes are used to quote something from the flow of the article in a larger size to draw the reader into the article. This is different in purpose to a blockquote where you want to include a longish quotation in the flow of the narrative. Additionally, these pull quote elements are automatically populated with links to share on Twitter and Facebook.</p>

<pre><code>&lt;p class="pull-quote" data-quote="...there is nothing in the world so irresistibly contagious as laughter and good humour."&gt;
    It is a fair, even-handed, noble adjustment of things, that while there is infection in disease and sorrow, there is nothing in the world so irresistibly contagious as laughter and good humour.
&lt;/p&gt;
</code></pre>

<p>You may provide a custom tweet quote using the <code>data-quote</code> attribute. However, if the <code>data-quote</code> attribute is not present — or left blank — then the tweet quote will be created automatically; if required, it will be truncated to fit within 140 characters.</p>

<h3 id="thumbnail-gallery">Thumbnail gallery</h3>

